block content
    h1 Parameter estimation

    h2#what-is-parameter-estimation What is parameter estimation?

    p
        | Parameter estimation is the process of finding the distribution parameters that best explain
        | an observed dataset. ranjs uses #[strong maximum likelihood estimation (MLE)]: it finds the
        | parameter values that maximise the probability of seeing the data under the assumed model.
        | This is done by a derivative-free Nelder-Mead simplex optimizer, which makes it robust to
        | distributions with non-smooth or discontinuous likelihoods.

    p
        | Once parameters are estimated you can inspect them, compare models by AIC/BIC, or run a
        | built-in goodness-of-fit test — all with the same distribution instance returned by
        | #[code fit()].

    h2#full-workflow The full workflow

    p
        | #[code fit()] closes the full statistical cycle: define a model, generate (or collect) data,
        | estimate parameters from that data, then test whether the fit is adequate.

    pre: code.language-javascript.
        import { dist } from 'ranjs'

        // 1. Define and sample
        const model = new dist.Normal(3, 1).seed(42)
        const data  = model.sample(500)

        // 2. Fit parameters from data via MLE
        const fitted = dist.Normal.fit(data)
        console.log(fitted.p)           // { mu: 3.000, sigma: 1.000 }

        // 3. Test goodness of fit
        console.log(fitted.test(data))  // { statistics: 0.031, passed: true }

    p
        | The same pattern works for any distribution in the library. Here is a discrete example
        | fitting a Poisson model to count data:

    pre: code.language-javascript.
        import { dist } from 'ranjs'

        const data   = new dist.Poisson(4.2).seed(42).sample(200)
        const fitted = dist.Poisson.fit(data)
        console.log(fitted.p)           // { lambda: 4.225 }
        console.log(fitted.test(data))  // { statistics: 2.471, passed: true }

    h2#static-method Static method

    p.callout
        strong Note:
        |  #[code fit()] is a #[strong static] method called on the class, not on an instance.
        | Use #[code dist.Normal.fit(data)], not #[code model.fit(data)].

    table
        thead
            tr
                th Correct
                th Wrong
        tbody
            tr
                td: code dist.Normal.fit(data)
                td: code model.fit(data)   // TypeError

    h2#all-distributions All distributions

    p
        | All 140 exported distributions support #[code fit()]. Most have a data-aware
        | #[code static _fitInit(data)] override that seeds the Nelder-Mead optimizer from a
        | method-of-moments estimate, improving convergence reliability. The base-class fallback
        | uses random positive-value retries when no override is present.

    p
        | Zero-parameter distributions (e.g. #[code Gilbrat], #[code HalfLogistic]) skip
        | optimisation entirely: #[code Cls.fit(data)] simply returns #[code new Cls()].

    h2#goodness-of-fit Goodness of fit

    p
        | The instance returned by #[code fit()] is a fully-featured distribution object. You can
        | chain any distribution method on it:

    pre: code.language-javascript.
        const fitted = dist.Gamma.fit(data)

        fitted.test(data)        // KS goodness-of-fit test
        fitted.aic(data)         // Akaike information criterion
        fitted.bic(data)         // Bayesian information criterion
        fitted.pdf(x)            // density at any point
        fitted.sample(100)       // generate new variates from the fitted model

    p
        | See the #[a(href="index.html") API reference] for the full list of methods available on
        | every distribution instance.

